I'll start by executing the first tool in the workflow - the file reader to get our input data.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll first execute the data_processing_parser to prepare the data for transformation, using the output from our file reader operation as input.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the file_operations_scanner is the most relevant tool for detecting file formats, I'll use it to determine the format of our input file before attempting to parse it again.

<tool_call>file_operations_scanner
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the scanner didn't provide format information in its output, I'll modify the options to specifically request format detection. I'll execute the scanner again with additional parameters.

<tool_call>file_operations_scanner
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "scan_type": "format_detection"
  }
}
</tool_call>

                        I notice the scanner still isn't returning the file format information. Since we're not getting the expected output, I'll proceed with the original parser but specify the format explicitly as a fallback approach.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
